column169: No suggestion is offered, since the pressure relief valve operated as it was designed.

column168: A rolloff box containing this sludge material had been in a warming hut for several days prior to pickup to enable the frozen material to unload easily.  When the driver raised the box onto the hoist to load it onto the trailer, approximately 3 gallons of liquid material which had separated during the warming process leaked between the cover and the tailgate of the box.  The loading was done in containment.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and put the material and an absorbent into a nearby rolloff box containing the same material.  The shipment then proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The warming hut will no longer be used to thaw out the loads prior to shipment, ensuring no free liquids separate from the material and have the potential to leak.

Driver arrived at the ten day storage facility of the intended waste disposal facility after picking up multiple shipments of hazardous waste.  While conducting a routine post trip inspection, he noticed a small leak on the floor of the trailer.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the leaking drum into a suitable salvage container along with the absorbent material used to contain the spilled material.  The trailer then was accepted into the ten day storage facility of the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The driver recalled that when loading the trailer, the shipper's personnel pushed against the drums with the forklift to make room for the remaining drums.  At the time, no damage was noticed.  However, it was determined that the lock ring on one of the drums had been damaged by the action causing the seal to be compromised and begin leaking.  The material had also separated in transit, and some liquid subsequently was what leaked out.  The shipper was notified of the incident and advised they would discontinue the practice and also review their operations to insure the waste is dried out.

column168: When unloading totes from a trailer we found about 10 kg of material on the floor of the trailer. The leaking tote was identified and secured in a safe location. The leaking tote will be transfered to a clean empty tote.

An ITC loading operator was loading a Methanol car (ACFX 75708) on Rail Loading Rack B2. Shortly after startup, he noticed product coming from the belly valve  The loader immediately shutdown the product movement and realized that the belly valve on the railcar was sealed in the OPEN position.  Standard operating practice is for the rail car belly valve to be sealed in the closed position. The valve is clearly marked to identify OPEN and CLOSED positions. The loading operator is trained to verify valve position regardless of the seal, but failed to do so.
column169: Re-train operator importance of following each step of loading procedure and  checklist.  Refresher training will be conducted on all Rail Loading operators to re-emphasize working at a safe pace, not skipping procedural steps, etc.

On 02/06/2011 at 17:36 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Hookers Point yard in Tampa, FL, discovered GATX 203787, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Amaizing Energy LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2011-02-06-00045. Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and observed product dripping from around the liquid line valve stem. In addition, the liquid line valve operating handle was in the open position. Eagle/SWS closed the valve and tightened the packing retainer to secure the container. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Jeff Eliason 651-355-8525.     This incident did not require a special switching move.   A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is required for this incident.    Cause Code: 296   NARRI: 2(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 32

On 02/10/2011 at 11:44 hrs., CSXT Hazardous Material Manager discovered NATX 364316, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking liquid from the bottom of the rail car. The shipper, Adkins Energy LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2011-02-10-0007. The bottom outlet valve (BOV) cap  was less than tool tight and product was leaking from the threads of the BOV cap. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mert Green 815-369-4663. The BOV cap was loosened and drained of all product and the cap was tool tightened stopping the leak. The car was then released for transportation to destination.    This incident does not require a special switching move.   A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident    Cause code: 149  NARRI: 5 (3+3+0) x (2+0) = 60

The car was isolated and the shipper, PCS Sales, was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2011-02-13-00050. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a  by 6 weld seam breach near the top of the BR side 1st hopper chute. CSXT will arrange for repairs after the railcar is unloaded.      This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause code and NARRI information is not applicable for this release.

column168: On 02/18/2011 at 15:00 hrs., personnel at the CSXT Radnor yard in Nashville, TN discovered GATX 5969, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking liquid from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated in the rail yard away from CSXT employees and the shipper, Marsulex Inc., was notified thru CHEMTREC Report 2011-02-18-00111. Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line was open and the plug was less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Tom Mills 419-698-8181. Eagle/SWS closed the valve, tightened the plug and the leak stopped. The car was then released for transport to destination.    This incident did require a special switch move. column168: Pantry Maintenance issue. Delivery was below 90%. Fitting and/or Hose did not disconnect. Per driver, David Harper (Trainer), well filled up and overflowed as he  was reaching the end of delivering 2800 gallons RUL. Veedor Root shows that we were  outside 90%. Shows that 90% ullage was 456 gallons after delivery. Catoosa County Fire Dept and Ringgold police responded. Per Deputy Chief of Fire Dept, no cleanup other than what we did was/is needed. Jacob and I were at the scene shortly after incident occurred. We did end up dropping 284 gallons RUL into the mid-grade tank. Will need to "fix" that on next delivery. When driver noticed product overflowing, he quickly shut off the flow of product. Product was still overflowing so he switched drop fitting from RUL tank to Mid-Grade tank to relieve pressure in tank and keep product in hose from hitting the ground. This allowed some product to spill but probably stopped the overflow faster than anything else.

Driver uses his assigned product hoses and tractor air to make delivery.  He uses 11 sections of 2 inch by 20 feet hoses to do this.  The driver discovered the leak at the connection of number 2 and 3 hoses.  Driver stopped the product transfer, released the pressure and uncoupled the hoses.  He found that there was a missing hose gasket in the female end of number three hose.  2-3 gallons of product spilled and was contained on the process floor.  Driver and plant operator cleaned up the spilled material. driver replaced the   missing gasket and continued with delivery.
column169: Driver has many years experience with this type of work and cannot explain why he missed the gasket issue. driver will he retrained and issued disciplinary action in accordance with established company policy

GATX 6371 was discovered leaking at Pasadena Yard at 1517 hours on 2/2/11 by yard crews. Agrifos was notified and M&M Protection was called to respond to the leak. Aprroximately 2 gallons of product had leak out of the 8" fill hole due to a faulty gasket and one of four bolts being loose. Agrifos personel replaced the gasket and sealed the fill hole. M&M Protection remediated the area by washing down the car and surrounding area with a base solution to return the pH to normal ranges. The scene was cleared at 1750 hours.
column169: Agrifos is investigating the leak and will advise.

column168: At 1006 hours on 2/22/11 a stron odor was reported in the middle of PTRA Pasadena Yard. It was determined the DUPX 29205 had vapors bypassing the gasket on the manway cover. Intercontinental Terminals Company was notified and responded to the scene. They removed the dome bolts and discovered that the teflon gasket was not sealing properly and was allowing the vapors to bypass the gasket when the car was moved. They replaced the gasket and sealed the tank car for transport at  1235 hours.
column169: ITC stated that they are in the process of changing over to a sturdy gasket and stopping use of the thin teflon gasket found on the DUPX 29205.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Odor was reported to the PTRA North Yard Yardmaster at 1340 hours on 2/25/2011. After inspection it was determined that DUPX 29217 was the source of the odor. Intercontinental Terminals Company was notified and responded to the scene at 1505 hours. They determined that several dome bolts were hand tight and that the gasket was cut. They replaced the gasket and sealed the tank car properly. Scene was cleared at 1530 hours. No product was spilled.
column169: ITC is investigating the incident with Dupont

column168: Driver was operating a CTMV in a left hand curve. The right side tires got off the right side edge of the road ontosofter soil and the CTMV rolled over on its right side. As the CTMV rolled over it struck some pine trees breakingfront and rear vent line piping, and creating a couple of vertical 12" cuts in the tank shell. Emergency responderswere called with vacuum tanks and were on the scene within an hour. They began to pump oil out of the overturnedCTMV onto another and vacuuming up oil puddling on the ground. The area was diked to contain the spill fromspreading. The remediation response included 80 bbl of free products, snow, and dirt were recovered. About 1500tons of soil will be excavated, and the remedial work is in progress.

column168: On Friday, February 25, 2011, at 1645 hours EST, Mr. Eric Nelson, from Southern Refrigerated Transport contacted American Compliance Technologies, Inc. (A•C•T) Nationwide Project Manager, Mr. Gary L. Weiss to request assistance with a leaking drum of Benzyl Salicyate (UN 3082, Environmentally Hazardous Substances). The spill occurred at 2723 Carl Road in Irving, Texas. Mr. Nelson advised that Tracy Shuler, the Souther Refrigeraed driver noticed an odor coming from the trailer. , At this point an unknown amount of product was released inside the trailer.  Mr. Weiss contacted Mr. Shuler, to determine if any product had leaked out of the trailer.  Mr. Shuler reported that no product has leaked out of the trailer. At this time no regulatory reporting was required due to the unknown amount of product lost.    Our response team began the cleanup process by marking the leak point on the drum and placing it into a an over pack drum.  The contaminated pallets was removed from the trailer and placed into a 55-gallon drum.  Sorbents were used to clean the trailer floor.    Once the floor was cleaned the sorbents and PPE were added to the drum of pallets for disposal.    Per Mr. Eric Nelson, the over packed drum was reloaded into the trailer, properly blocked and braced for continued transport.     WASTE DISPOSAL    As a result of the response activities, one (1) 55-gallon drum of contaminated wood, PPE and sorbents was generated.  All waste was disposed at a permited facility.

A semi-trailer of containers was brought into the Veolia ES Technical Solutions facility located in Menomonee Falls, WI on February 11, 2011. As the drums on the trailer were being offloaded, a Veolia employee became aware of a leak on the trailer. Upon further investigation, it was discovered that a drum containing gasoline and diesel fuel mix was leaking. The leak occured as a result of the drum being very old and rusted. The drum was then overpacked and the spill cleaned up and placed into the overpack drum.
column169: This incident was reviewed with field personnel and drivers to emphasize the need to thoroughly check each container's integrity prior to shipping.

column168: A small plastic removable top container was being transferred from one trailer to another at the Veolia facility located in Menomonee Falls, WI. While moving a pallet containing the plastic container, the container tipped over and fell off the pallet. As a result the free liquid in the container leaked from the lid seal. The container was overpacked into another container and the spill was cleaned up and placed within the overpack as well.
column169: The original container was not rated for free liquids. This was communicated to the original generator and carrier. In addition, Veolia field personnel were instructed to overpack any container they observed that contained free liquids and was not rated to contain free liquids.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making a delivery to the Brunton School, approximately 56 gallons of free product were released.  The cause of the release was an overfill due to a driver error.  The release impacted a small amount of soil and an asphalt parking lot.  Western Mass Environmental of West Springfield, Massachusetts was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Western Mass Environmental applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the impacted asphalt surface.  Western Mass Environmental recovered the spent absorbent material and placed into drums for disposal.  Additional site cleanup is pending. No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, United Transport of East Longmeadow will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column169: BE AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS!  RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.  WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ESPECIALLY THE LONG BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING THE VARIOUS PACKAGES.  FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT.  DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK AND WHILE  TRANSFERING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS!  DRUMS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGE AND PUNCTURING.

column168: On 02/17, the Lincolnshire IL. Fire Department Dispatch Centre notified the CN Regional Operation Centre of a strong odor coming from a train stopped on CN's mainline adjacent to the towns of Buffalo Grove and Wheeling, IL (WAUKESHA SUB MP30.25). The train, A4681-17 (41L 29E 5912T 4206') was stretched north from Wheeling into Buffalo Grove,  there was no crew on the train at the time. CN's response team responded, while en route to the scene and in communication with fire department Incident Commander, it was determined that the odor was coming from the 38th car in the train GATX 23517 (L/ Turpentine, UN 1993, class 3/PG III). Upon further inspection by CN's response team, all appropriate valves, covers and housing were closed and seals intact. One manway bolt was noted less than tool tight allowing product vapor to pass, excessive dried product was noted around the manway and on the east side of the car.  The bottom outlet valve cap was also found less than tool tight (six full turns), but no liquid product was noted. Manway and cap secured, car released at 2300 hours to destination.

A Trans Carriers tractor trailer experienced a load shift.  This caused three 5-gallon buckets of paint to be damaged.  Approximately 11 gallons of paint was released inside the trailer.  An environmental contractor, SWS, was hired for cleanup.  They arrived at the release site, Sherwin Williams Distribution Center at 400 Winterhaven Blvd, Winter Haven, FL for cleanup.  They unloaded the cargo and cleaned the trailer.  The Sherwin Williams personnel were going to containerize the cargo for transportation.  SWS left site with one drum of impacted absorbents for disposal.

On 02/28, CN transportation department employee noted product coming from the top of tank car UTLX 667372(L / FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S.- XYLENE) during switching operations at the CN Markham Yard, East Hazel Crest, IL. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. All cover, housing and valve seals intact. CN's response team responded noting half of the manway cover gasket missing / deteriorated, one bolt less than tool tight allowing product to escape during movement. New manway gasket installed, manway cover secured and the tank car released for movement.

column168: GATX 16617 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported expelling product from its top fitting area during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement of GATX 16617 was stopped and after a visual inspection it was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard for furtherance. No product was observed leaking while GATX 16617 remained motionless. Spillage on the side shell was drying and no ground impact of any spillage was reported. The shipper was notified, sending repair responders from RESCAR. Responders reported that the 165 psi frangible disc had ruptured. The frangible disc was replaced in kind during the morning of 2/05/2011. All other valves and fittings were inspected with only one exception noted. The manway gasket was found with a very small tear in the nozzle lip overhang area which did not affect the sealing properties of the gasket. A new gasket was applied and the manway cover was resecured.

column168: EMPLOYEES WORKING IN THE UPS PLEASANTDALE HUB REPORTED HEARING A LOUD NOISE AND WITHIN SECONDS SEEING A PACKAGE APPROACHING ON THE CONVEYOR BELT IN FLAMES.  THEY DESCENDED FROM THEIR WORK PLATFORM AS A SUPERVISOR TRIGGERED THE FIRE ALARM TO EVACUATE THE BUILDING AND CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  TWO ADDITIONAL EMPLOYEES ARRIVED AT THE SCENE OF THE FIRE WITH FIRE ENTINGUISHERS AND WORKED TO EXTINGUISH THE BURNING PACKAGE, WHICH HAD COME TO REST ON A METAL CHUTE.  AT LEAST ONE OF THE BOTTLES IN THE PACKAGE BURST IN THE HEAT OF THE FLAMES AND THE SPREADING FIRE ACTIVATED THE SPRINKLER SYSTEM.  A COMBINATION OF 15 FIRE EXTINGUISHERS AND THE SPRINKLER SYSTEM EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE FROM THE ORIGINAL PACKAGE AND A FEW THAT WERE INCIDENTALLY IGNITED IN THE INCIDENT.  UPS IS UNABLE TO DETERMINE THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE PRODUCT LEAKAGE WHICH LED TO THE FIRE.  REMNANTS OF FOUR BOTTLES WERE COLLECTED DURING CLEAN-UP.
column169: WITHOUT BEING ABLE TO ASSIGN A DEFINITIVE CAUSE, UPS HAS NO RECOMMENDATIONS.

On 2/25/11 at approximately 11:00 hours IMTT-Bayonne had just completed loading an AJ Weigand tank trailer with Ethyl Acrylate when it was discovered that the lower internal valve was leaking.  IMTT Operations personnel quickly placed a 5-gallon pail under the trailer compartment to collect dripping product however there was more vapor being released than liquid product.  The contents of the trailer was then off loaded back into the original above ground storage tank.  The trailer with the defective internal valve was released by IMTT and arrangements were made to bring in another trailer and resume the operation.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident. The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company  and will address any mechanical or structural issues with the truck or related components.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Missing Component or Device
column168: On 02/22/2011 at 14:45 hrs., FRA Inspector David Snyder discovered GATX 61006, a loaded tank car of Aluminum Chloride, Solution, with evidence of a release on the side of the container in CSXT Cayce yard in Cayce, SC. The car was isolated and the shipper, Albemarle Corporation, was contacted via CHEMTREC report 2011-02-22-00151.  The shipper's representative, Brad Thomas 225-388-7104, dispatched a response team and found the cause of the release was due to a missing pressure relief device frangible disc.  On 2/23/2011, the shipper's crew replaced the frangible disc and secured the container for transit.      This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 437  NARRI: 5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

column25: ADM Corn Processing - Wet Corn Plant
column168: This report covers a 32 car derailment involving a total net loss of material of approximately  786,245 gallons.  The total costs associated with this incident are approximate pending final remediation:  material loss at $2.50 per gallon = $1,965,612; response and remediation = $2,000,000.  30 of 32 tank cars suffered tank shell failure and total loss of contents due to derailment damage or the subsequent fire.    There was an initial evacuation of 25 people for 8 hours.  Less than 10 of these 25 were evacuated for 48 hours.    The attached spreadsheet outlines each car number, the amount of material shipped and the amount recovered.      The attached photograph depicts the incident site with tank car positions identified.     Multiple emergency response and remediation contractors responded to this incident.  Remediation and site monitoring efforts are ongoing.

Residue tank car UTLX 500073 was noted by West Virginia State Hazmat Inspector Danny McCourt with a small product vapor release from the vacum relief valve.  The car was isolated and the shipper notified. Shipper representatives responded and found the vacum relief valve had a defective O-ring.  The valve was removed and a threaded plug installed to stop the release. The car is currently being held awaiting a DOT Movement Approval to move the car to a shop for repair or replacement of the defective valve.

On February 24th, 2011, Trans Carriers reported a UN1133 Flammable Adhesive release that impacted the trailer floor. Approximately 15 gallons of adhesive was released. Absorbent pads were utilized to clean the area and the waste was containerized for disposal.

WHILE EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING A TOTE CONTAINER; EMPLOYEE DID NOT RECOGNIZE THAT THE CORNER OF THE TOTE, WAS GOING TO BE RESTING ON THE LIFT GATE ONCE THE TOTE WAS LOWERED WITH A HAND JACK. THIS LOWERING ACTION CAUSED THE TOTE TO STRIKE THE LIFT GATE; OVERTURN AND RELEASE MATERIAL INTO THE FACILITY'S SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PIT. PRODUCT WAS IMMEADIATELY RECLAIMED AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.
column169: RECOMMEND REVEIWING UNLOADING PROCEDURES WITH EMPLOYEE FOR ADEQUACY.

column168: On February 26th, 2011, R&L Carriers reported a leaking 55-gallon drum of UN1866 resin in their trailer. The resin impacted the trailer floor and an asphalt parking lot. Granular absorbents were applied to the release and the waste was containerized for disposal. The damaged drum was overpacked and left on the trailer for continued transportation.

The driver reported that he was using air pressure and 60ft of hose to unload from cargo tank into customer storage tank. When the storage tank was almost full, he closed the discharge valve and then opened it just one turn to reduce flow.  Within 2 seconds of the hose going empty, he closed the valve.  At that time, the customer's PVC fill line where the our hose was connected, failed.  Hose came off and sprayed some product.  The driver estimated 5 gallons but that is probably over estimated.  No injuries to anyone.  Customer cleaned up.
column169: The fill line had recently been replaced and this was just the second time it was used.  Customer will take that into account to see if any changes need to be made when it is replaced.

column168: TELX 73230 was noted by carrier personnel with product dripping from the bottom of the car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Eagle/SWS, responded and found material dripping from the bottom outlet valve flange due to a defective gasket.  Efforts to stop the release were unsuccessful.    The contents of the car was transferred to another rail car.  TELX 73230 will be sent to a shop for repairs under FRA Movement Approval.

After minor running repairs were completed to the brake and coupler appliances on AMCX 25745 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car), AMCX 25745 was being pulled from the repair track in the railyard when a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder observed a product slosh emanating from the manway closure during this movement. The movement was stopped and the responder instructed AMCX 25745 to be carefully moved back to the repair track area for a detailed securement inspection. Inspection of the manway closure revealed that the manway gasket applied was crimped with a section of the gasket (approximately 1/4 of the gasket circumference) folded over. The responder applied a new manway gasket and tool tightened all manway securement bolts. Intact seal INEOS 119745 was replaced by seal numbered 1095270. Drying spillage on the side shell was wiped and no ground impact was observed.  No further product release was observed from AMCX 25745 during subsequent movements in the railyard.  The side specification stencil on AMCX 25745 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2001 and next due in 2011.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column25: DIAMANT AGUILA MEXICANA SA DE CV
column168: RESPONDED TO A SHIPMENT IN IMPORT INSPECT AREA. CUSTOMS AGENT DISCOVERED (1) 1 QUART CAN OF BOAT GLUE. NO LEAK. NO SIGNS OF ABUSE TO OUTER CARTON. HELD FOR FAA INSPECTION

Our vehicle was stopped at the Georgia Dept of Transportation Scales at Lavonia, Ga for a CVSA Inspection. During the inspection process the officer discovered a small amount of lead material on the side of a drum and on top of the pallet under the drum. The officer wrote on the inspection report a release of a hazardous material from its package. He contributed the release to a loose ring around the drum. The non-bulk package this material was in was a 55 gallon steel drum that contained apx. 900 pounds of this material.       Our investigation determined the material was spilled at the shipper during the process of loading the material into the drum. It was not spilled while loading the truck nor was there a package failure. (The pictures taken show the material on the side of the drum and on top of the pallet next to the drum. There was stretch-wrapping placed around the drums by the shipper before it was loaded into the truck. The material is under the stretch-wrapping.)    The material was in a semi-molten state when it was spilled onto the side of the drum. It had hardened before being placed onto the truck for transportation. The material was contained where it at hardened onto the drum and the pallet. The spilled material was removed by the receiver and recycled with the material that was in the drums.
column169: We contacted the shipper of the material after the event. The event was investigated with their assistance. During this investigation it was determined that the material was spilled while the drum was being loaded at their facility. They informed us they have implemented additional procedures to prevent material being filled into the drums to escape.    We will also re-emphasize to our drivers the importance of being alert to any evidence that may indicate a potential presence of a leaking container or spilled material.

column168: Please note, BAX Global, Inc. shall be named as reporting party only.    According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading at the Swanton, OH HUB facility one skid containing four steel drums of which three contained one hundred and eighty-nine liters and one of seventy-five liters of UN1263, Paint, III, of which one drum of seventy-five liters was damaged by a forklift puncture.  Approximately one liter of product released impacting the skid and warehouse concrete floor.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel used gloves and shovels to contain and cleanup the spill using four absorbent pads.  Approximately one eighty-five gallon plastic salvage drum was generated including the drum, cleanup materials and paint soiled absorbent pads which is intended to be forwarded to the shipper.  The remaining shipment will be forwarded to the consignee.  No injuries or exposures.  The MSDS was requested.
column169: BAX Global, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Driver unloaded his load in the wrong tank - He thought he opened the valve on the correct tank but actually only opened the tank outlet, causing the tanks to run over by approx. 63 gallons - Driver was given three days off from work - Tanks were cleaned with various agents, contaminted soil was removed from site and replaced with fresh soil
column169: supervisor states that better valve alignment, better communication from pipeline and locking out sour headers if station is down may prevent a future occurrance such as this one

column168: Truck driver accepted these drums from customer and upon arrival at the Fort Wayne service center, it was noticed the drums were bulging and getting warm. The shipper was notified and Chem Trec was called on their behalf. The product began to leak at the vent and was isolated until third party spill response arrived. Complete containment was provided. The customer sent a chemist to analyze the product for the reaction that was taking place. After 24 hours the product cooled and the outer area of the 3 drums was deconned. Minimal leakage and all spilled material was contained to the trailer floor. Deveco claimed custody of the material at this point for transfer back to manufacturing facility.

column168: Driver staged the transport to be unloaded at customer. column169: Driver was unaware the Internal Valve was stuck in the open position until he opened the 3" cap on the discharge line.  Drivers have been instructed to open discharge lines cautiously with one-ear open and one-hand covering the cap to release any pressure and/or product that may have leaked into the product discharge lines during transit.  Reinterated the importance of the utilization of Full PPE's in situations of this nature.

column168: After arrival in the railyard from an inbound BNSF train, GATX 6667 (DOT 111A100W2 tank car) was reported with fresh product on its side shell which was dripping onto the ground ballast. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected GATX 6667. Responders reported all shipper seals were intact. The liquid line's closure cap was found as the product leak source. This closure cap was approximately 4 turns loose and it was tool tightened which ended any further product release. Spillage observed on the ground was neutralized. Spillage on the side shell of GATX 6667 was neutralized and washed at the locomotive servicing area in the railyard.

column168: On February 23, 2011, a Quality Carriers tanker rolled over onto the highway.  The tanker was carrying UN3264 a corrosive liquid.  This caused the release of approximately 2 gallons of product and an additional 2 gallons of motor oil.  There was no release of diesel fuel.  The release impacted the asphalt highway.  No soils, storm drains, or surface waters were impacted by the release.     United States Environmental Services (USES) had been dispatched to the scene to contain and secure the site; and provide initial cleanup and remediation activities.   On February 23, 2011, USES arrived on scene for assessment.  They first tightened the dome lid to prevent any additional product leak.  Absorbents were used to collect the small amount of motor oil and product released to the roadway.  The highway patrol had closed the southbound lanes until the tanker could be transferred.  A second Quality Carriers tanker arrived on site at approximately 2300 hours.  At that time, USES performed the tanker transfer.  Once the product had been removed, the wrecker service removed the damaged tanker from the roadway.  The closed lanes were re-opened, and the area was returned to original condition.

Driver entered rest stop on I-44. Driver advised CHEMTREC that there was a strong odor that irritated his eyes. Local Fire/EMT and Police responded to the rest area and set up a containment area around the vehicle. Driver was treated on site and then transferred to a hospital for both treatment of burns on his hands and possible inhalation of vapors. Driver was kept overnight for observations and released the next day with topical medication for his hands.   Incident commander was contacted by ERTS (carrier's emergency response management company) to determine if further assistance was required. ERTS was advised that I-44 WB was shut down as a precautionary measure and that traffic was diverted to a service road.  As additional assistance was requested, ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to the scene. After local Haz-Mat units completed their evaluation, environmental contractor was allowed to inspect the intermediate bulk containers (IBCs). THe IBCs were visually inspected, loose closures were tightened and the IBCs were staged on poly sheeting in the rest area. The trailer was inspected for free liquids, with none being found. After reinspection of the IBCs, the IBCs were loaded back onto the trailer and the load was secured.  A relief driver was dispatched by the carrier to allow the tractor/trailer to continue on its journey.     Please note that data related to release amount and phase are assumptions as no definitive data regarding the amount nor mechanism of release have been determined.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering unleaded gas to a customer location. The driver stuck the tank and upon unloading noticed that the tank filled after only 1900 gallons although his stick reading showed the tank had 6347 gallons of space available. The driver shut off flow of product. The driver then attempted to release the pressure off the hose by loosening the lock down on the tank. This caused product to leak from the hose and overfill tank into the containment area. Approximately 50 gallons leaked. The fire department and ADEM were called to the scene. The site was cleaned up by all personnel. It was determined that the tanks had a vapor tight recovery system which causes pressure build up and inaccurate stick readings. The driver needed to go by veeder root readings and not only stick readings. The driver followed prodcedure until he broke the seal between the lockdown and the tank.
column169: The driver was retrained on unloading procedures. All drivers were required to attend a safety meeting on how to follow procedures, including covering stick and veeder root readings, and what to do if a tank fills up.

column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: During normal switching operations in the railyard, a BNSF switchman reported product vapor/fumes emanating from ASTX 2010 (DOT 111A100W2 tank car). A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was notified and immediately inspected ASTX 2010. The responder reported that the 165 psi frangible disc in the safety vent had ruptured. The responder replaced the frangible disc in kind. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Spillage on the tank shell and observed ground impact area were neutralized. Intact seal at the rupture disc housing numbered 1736860 was replaced with seal BNSF 002468.

Driver was traveling west bound on Singleton Blvd. The city of Dallas had a ruptured waterline leaking onto the roadway. Due to the temperature being below freezing, the leaking water caused an ice patch on the road. The driver did not see the ice patch. When he hit the ice, he lost control of the vehicle. the vehicle slid sideways.When the tires gained traction on dry ground, the momentum caused the vehicle to overturn on the passenger side.  The impact and subsequent slide on the asphalt ruptured the #1 compartment. The drivers supervisor, police, and fire department were immediately notified. NRC was then notified, as was TCEQ. TAS environmental was called to the scene to begin cleaning up the spill.

On 2/23 at 3:00 PM, while attempting to break down an Occidential Chemical tank car GATX 22445 that was spotted toward the east end of track # 566 containing 156,400 lbs of Sodium Hydroxide Solutions 50% (Class 8; UN 1824; PG II), TRANSFLO - Cleveland East Ops Manager - Mike Nelson was sprayed with product from the tank car liquid education line valve assembly without a tank car fitting being applied. Lead Operator - Mike Vouk who was working on a tank car in the vicinity heard the commotion and saw that Mr. Nelson was in distress on the top of GATX 22445. Mr. Nelson was able to successfully get down off the top of the tank car’s platform, as product continued to spray from the aforementioned valve assembly. Mr. Vouk went to the ‘steam access’ side of the car in anticipation of ascending the railcar from that side, he then determined that the other side of the car would have the least risk for exposure and returned back to the north side of Track #556 (area by the office) and ascended the tank car’s ladder. Mr. Vouk was then able to safely shut off the liquid education line/standpipe valve and minimize the release of material. At this point in time Mr. Nelson shredded his PPE which included: Chemical Protective Acid Gear (Overalls and Jacket; Hard Hat; Face Shield; Chemical Spash Goggles, Chemical Resitant Gloves; etc.). Mr. Vouk then proceeded to escort Mr. Nelson to the office industrial shower/bathroom facility, where Mr. Nelson proceeded to rinse out his eyes in the sink and utilize the shower which did not have ample water available (e.g., obstructed water line). Mr. Vouk then contacted Cleveland’s CSR/Coordinator, Ms. Helen Longo who previous left for the day via her cell phone, where he request her to contact 911 and have an ambulance dispatched to the terminal immediately. Mr. Vouk then proceeded to escort Mr. Nelson to A&R Transport (neighboring business), in order to utilize their facility’s safety shower and eyewash station. While over at A&R, Mr. Vouk then asked them to ensure that 911 was dispatched to the TRANSFLO - Cleveland East terminal within the CSX Collinwood rail yard off East  152nd Street. Mr. Vouk then left Mr. Nelson over at A&R Transportation in order to retrieve the MSDS for Occidential Chemical’s Sodium Hydroxide Solutions 50%. At this point in time, ~ 3:20 PM, Local Police, EMS and Fire Department arrived onsite to treat Mr. Nelson and transport him to the local hospital (Metro Health Medical  Center Burn Unit). Mr. Vouk was encouraged by the Fire Dept to decontaminate his clothing and get checked out by their EMS, which included checking his vital signs. Mr. Vouk declined any further medical assistance and provided the product specific MSDS to the Fire Department, where they then proceeded to douse the tank car GATX 22445 with water along with the vicinity in order to dilute the alkalinity of the caustic soda. Mr. Vouk then depressurized GATX 22445 by opening the tank car’s vapor/air induction valve assembly thus all
column169: Conduct a comprehensive re-evaluation of Corrosive handling practices, which includes:  - Understanding basic chemistry (pH 0-14 scale, 7 neutral; acids versus alkali/bases)  - Chemical characteristics and hazards associated with handling class 8 Corrosives  - Routes of exposure (e.g., Inhalation; Ingestion; Absorption, Eye/Skin Contact)  - First Aid Measures (e.g., proper decontaminate soiled garments; flush affected area with copious amounts of water via emergency safety shower/eye wash station; seek medical assistance, 911)   - Prescribed PPE (e.g., Chemical Resistant Suit; Chemical Impervious Gloves; Steel Toed Rubber/Over Boots; Hard Hat w/Face Shield; Chemical Splash Goggles) Availability, Proper Usage, Care, Maintenance & Storage; Adequate Inventory Levels  - Emergency Safety Shower/Eye Wash Stations, staged within 50’/10 seconds of corrosive handling area with tepid water (>60ºF - <100ºF);  copious amount of water (minimum flushing rate of 0.4 gpm for eyewash, and 20 gpm for shower with a duration of 15 minutes)  - Environmental supplies availability, inventory & usage (e.g., frost free water access for rinsing down soiled tank car platforms and fittings; spill pans placed underneath trailer’s crash box hose tubes; spill overpack kits stocked with water based absorbent booms, pads & pillows; pallet of water based inert (sand; vermiculite) granulated absorbent.  - Emergency Response strategies (confine, contain, clean-up     - Personal Hygiene Standards wash thoroughly after handling; decontaminate PPE, ensure to thoroughly rinse the article, inspect the integrity of the article as deemed necessary, dispose of soiled garments accordingly, do not eat, drink or smoke in work area.   - Review the content of existing transfer procedures (e.g, tank car set-up; method of transfer via regulated air pressure <35 PSI, tank car top to tank trailer top); caustic soda tank car heating via regulated steam pressure 15 PSI  - Conduct Retraining w/employees which handle Corrosive including HazCom module and transfer procedural training    Implementation date for the above corrective actions is:  4/30/2011

column168: A 55-gallon drum of UN2735 was punctured at the loading dock of a Forward Air Terminal in Denver, CO.  The terminal personnel contained the area until an environmental contractor arrived.  Environmental Restoration neutralized the area and used absorbents to collect the product.  The damaged drum and the materials were overpacked and taken off site for disposal.

Our driver was traveling east on I-80 when he heard of an accident ahead.  He was slowing when another truck passed him at a high rate of speed and then lost control.  This caused our driver to put on the brakes and then he started to jack knife.  Our trailer hit the existing accident that he had slowed down to avoid, and the other truck rolled over.    The pump on the belly of the trailer was impacted allowing LP vapor to escape.  The trailer was empty so only the retained vapor escaped into the atmosphere.
column169: Although another truck directly caused the accident, our driver should have slowed down even more than he did and anticipated that the road was slippery since there was already an accident at that location.    We will be retraining all of our drivers on driving too fast for conditions and being more aware of their surroundings.

column168: GATX 60233 was noted by carrier personnel with strong product odor in area of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, WEL Environmental, responded and found the manway cover gasket was cut and overlapped allowing product vapor to escape.  A second contractor, SPSI, responded on 2/21/11, and replaced the manway cover gasket stopping the release.    During the initial response phase of this incident two WEL employees and one carrier employee were exposed to product vapors sufficient to cause personal injuries.  One WEL employee and the carrier employee were hospitalized overnight and released without lost time.  One WEL employee was hospitalized four days and released and returned to work.      Note: this same car was noted releasing product vapor at the same location on 1/30/11.  The original defective manway cover gasket had been replaced during that response.

column168: Because of road conditions he detoured from hwy 40 onto hwy 189 westbound. Part way  down the canyon, the truck slid on ice and hit Guardrail, overturning the pup trailer into the median. Oil was transferred to another trailer. Tractor and trailer 376 was taken to 2/17/2011 The yard of Summit Oil on 2125 North Redwood Road. Salt Lake, Utah to be unloaded in the morning and then taken to L. W. Millers shop for repairs. The pup trailer was loaded on a trailer and was to be delivered to Beall trailer, in Salt Lake. Until we hear where Flying J  Wants us to take it. The Driver (Dustin) was taken home in a personal car where he filled out an accident report form and went in for a post accident drug test, and will wait the review board.    In review The Accident resulted in damage to the lead trailer and multiple damages to the pup trailer.  There was no Injury  There was no EPA clean up or contamination  Some guardrail damage to State property.

column25: HYUNDAI INTERMODAL INC. FOR LG ELECTRONICS INC.
column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Safety Inspector notified the BNSF intermodal facility in El Paso, TX that seven intermodal shipping containers on hand at   the BNSF intermodal hub awaiting outbound drayage to Mexico (Ciudad Juarez, Chihuahua, Mexico) contained undeclared hazardous material.   These seven intermodal containers were imported from Seoul, South Korea/Republic of Korea and originally billed by LG Electronics Inc. as   Electronic & Electrical Goods. The BNSF rail movement of these containers initiated in Los Angeles, CA and terminated in El Paso, TX.   Revised billing from LG Electronics Inc. through Hyundai Intermodal indicated that these seven containers contained UN 1219, Class 3, Packing   Group II Isopropyl Alcohol (a 3M Adhesion Promoter) as part of their lading.   The following revisions for inclusion of the Class 3 material were received;   Container HDMU 628801 1 drum 85 kg of Isopropyl Alcohol   Container HDMU 667372 1 drum 275 kg of Isopropyl Alcohol   Container HDMU 614629 1 drum 139 kg of Isopropyl Alcohol   Container HDMU 638137 1 drum 190 kg of Isopropyl Alcohol   Container DFSU 621845 1 drum 142 kg of Isopropyl Alcohol   Container GESU 636261 1 drum 280 kg of lsopropyl Alcohol   Container DFSU 621719 1 drum 70kg of Isopropyl Alcohol  ON 4/19/2011, BNSF WAS INFORMED BY THE FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SAFETY INSPECTOR THAT AFTER A THOROUGH INSPECTION OF ALL LADING INSIDE THE SEVEN INTERMODAL CONTAINERS (NOTED ABOVE); THE ONLY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FOUND IN EACH CONTAINER WAS AN ONE GALLON SIZED JERRICAN OF A FLAMMABLE LIQUID IDENTIFIED BY CONTENTS LABEL AS 3M 111 ADHESION PROMOTER CONTAINING ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL. THESE JERRUCANS DID NOT HAVE ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LABELS APPLIED TO THEM (SEE ATTACHED PHOYOGRAPHS).

column168: ON 02-11-2011 OUR DRIVER STEPHAN NUCICH WAS RETURNING TO OUR LANSING, MI TERMINAL WITH A LOAD OF LTL LINEHAUL FREIGHT.  AT 0630 AM EST I RECEIVED A CALL THAT HE HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT.  IT SEEMS THAT ANOTHER TRUCK HAD PULLED OFF THE ROADWAY TO CONDUCT MAINTENANCE - WHEN IT PULLED BACK ONTO THE ROAD IT WAS NOT YET UP TO SPEED WHEN MR. NUCUCH CAME UPON IT - NOT REALIZING THAT OTHER TRUCK WAS MOVING SLOW MR. NUCICH CLOSED THE GAP AND RAN INTO THE BACK OF THE OTHER VEHICLE AT HIGHWAY SPEEDS.  HE WAS ALERT AND TALKING AT THE SCENE HOWEVER THEY HAD TO CUT HIM OUT OF THE VEHICLE.  THE OTHER PARTIES WERE FINE AT THE SCENE.  I WAS INSTRUCTED BY A SGT CHRIS CURTVILLE OF THE BERRIEN COUNTY SHERRIF'S DEPARTMENT THAT THERE MAY HAVE BEEN SOME HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASED SO I IMMEDIATELY CALLED SAFETY KLEEN TO PROCESS THE SCENE.  ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT JOB #30037: ON 02-11-11 AT APPROXIMATELY 0745 (CTZ) MR. TIRSO BELTRAIN OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WAS CONTACTED BY SAFETY-KLEEN TO PROVIDE SERVICES TO EXPEDITED FREIGHT SYSTEMS, INC. (EFS).  AN EFS TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT. AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT, AN UNKNOWN LIQUID WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER. MR. BELTRAN CONTACTED SUNPRO SERVICES (AN ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT SUBCONTRACTOR) AND REQUESTED THAT SUNPRO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT.  THE INCIDENT WAS LOCATED ON INTERSTATE HIGHWAY 94 (EASTBOUND) AT MILE MARKER 4 NEAR NEW BUFFALO, MICHIGAN.  THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE.  THE TRAILER CONTAINED A  MIXED LOAD OF FREIGHT AND IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE RELEASE HAD OCCURRED TOWARDS THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  ABSORBENTS WERE APPLIED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO A LOADING DOCK TO ACCESS THE FREIGHT IN THE NOSE.  FREIGHT WAS UNLOADED.  IT WAS OBSERVED THAT CARDBOARD BOXES CONTAINING GLASS BOTTLES OF HEXANE PRODUCT HAD BEEN CRUSHED, HENCE CRUSHING THE GLASS CONTAINERS WITHIN THE CARDBORAD BOX.  THE CREW SEPARATED THE NONE DAMAGE CONTAINERS.  THE CRUSHED GLASS AND IMPACTED CARDBOARD BOXES AND ABSORBENTS WERE THEN PLACED INTO AN 85-GALLON OVERPACK DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS LABELED AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE SUBCONTRACTOR'S FACILITY PENDING DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS TO BE MADE BY SAFETY-KLEEN SYSTEMS, INC.
column169: WE HAVE CONDUCTED A COMPANY WIDE RE-TRAINING PROGRAM TO ALERT OUR DRIVERS TO THE DANGERS OF SLOW MOVING TRAFFIC - ESPECIALLY AT NIGHT AND IN INCLEMENT CONDITIONS.  THIS WAS A CASE WHERE MR. NUCICH SAW THE VEHICLE BUT DID NOT REALIZE HOW SLOW THE VEHICLE WAS MOVING UNTIL IT WAS TOO LATE.  WH HAVE RUN THIS LANE FOR THE LAST 15 YEARS AND HAVE ONLY HAD TWO ACCIDENTS IN THAT TIME.  WE CONSTANTLY MONITER OUR DRIVER FORCE TO ENSURE COMPLIANCE WITH ALL FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL REGULATIONS.

column168: Dock worker moved freight/packaging into the trailer using a forklift.  There were loose hanging straps on the interior wall. The outer packaging was a fiberboard box containing two 2.5 gallon plastic bottles.  The entire contents of both bottles, 5 gallons total, spilled onto the trailer floor and onto the ground. An employee in the Conway Safety Dept was contacted as well as Chemtrec (Report #20110226 00012).    After being advised by Chemtrec, a supervisor on-site, using PPEs, covered spill with absorbent, and transferred to waste container.  Waste container was moved to storage area within service center for disposal at a later date.

A BNSF train operating on main track derailed several railcars including SHPX 209988 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) that derailed on its side and came to rest at the rocky shoreline of the Puget Sound. The cause of the derailment was attributed to a broken wheel rim on the first railcar derailed. SHPX 209988 leaked product from the manway closure that had one manway securement bolt sheared off. The manway closure was facing towards the embankment and parallel to ground level. Also, liquid product leaked from the SHPX 209988's vacuum relief valve (VRV). Responders placed receptacles under the leak areas until the leaks were abated.  A manway securement bolt was fabricated, applied and secured to end the product release from the manway closure. The VRV orifice was plugged to end the product release from the VRV area. Responders neutralized spillage and on 2/28/2011 transferred the remaining product within SHPX 209988 into portable Frac tanks before tidal water levels engulfed the location where SHPX 209988 came to rest. After SHPX 209988 was emptied of its contents, it was removed from shoreline area and decontaminated. All impacted soils were excavated.

The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement with Hapag-Lloyd Container Line by NYK Line, on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Vietnam Express from New York, New York as the following:    - 2 Boxes of UN3267, Corrosive Liquid, Basic, Organic, NOS (N-Aminoethylpiperazine), Class 8, PG II.    - 8 Drums of UN1307, Xylenes, Class 3, PG III, FP 34C    - 2 Boxes of UN3267, Corrosive Liquid, Basic, Organic, NOS (N-Aminoethylpiperazine), Class 8, PG II    NYK advised Hapag-LLoyd after the vessel had sailed from New York that the freight container in fact did not contain UN1307 (Xylenes) and one of the UN3267.  However, it does contain:    UN1759, Corrosive Solid, NOS (Strontium Hydroxide, Octahydrate), Class 8, PG III    The shpping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not reflect the correct hazardous material loaded in the container.    NYK subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.

column168: During switching operations in the railyard, a BNSF switch crew reported a strong vinegar odor emanating near CELX 1266 (DOT 111S60ALW1 tank car). Afterwards, visual observation from the crew revealed that CELX 1266 was leaking product down its side shell. CELX 1266 was cordoned-off awaiting detailed inspection from hazardous material responders. Contract responders reported that the leak source was the liquid valve which was found in an open position with its closure plug not tool tight. The responders closed the liquid valve and tool tightened its closure plug. The liquid valve's operating handle was adjusted to fit under the closed valve housing cover when the operating handle was in the full closed position.  Spillage was neutralized and rinsed. The responders also reported that during their detailed inspection of CELX 1266 other securement deficiencies were corrected at the vapor valve closure plug and the securement nuts/bolts on all valve flanges. No further odor or product releases were reported from CELX 1266 during subsequent movements in the railyard.  Intact shipper seal SSC0229260 was replaced by seal numbered SRS000354.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Trimac driver announced over the radio to report to the Sulfur transfer area immediately.  All employees reported to the site and saw that 75 gallons of Molten Sulfur had been released from the vapor recovery sock on the false dome lid.  This was the 4th load into the railcar which should have held 55,900lbs before being full.  The loader who set up the railcar that morning stated that there was no obvious heel in the railcar during equipment set up.
column169: At this time the incident is still under investigation. The loader that inspected the railcar stated that they did not see an obvious heel inside the railcar. Due to the hazardous nature of this initial inspection (loaders are wearing a full face respirator and cannot break the plane of the confined space with their body) it is difficult to see into all areas of the railcar.    Inspection methods and tools are being tested to allow personnel to see inside the railcar, such as a lighted periscope, which can be placed into the railcar and give visibility without breaking the plane of the confined space.

column168: Employee was driving a Bobtail on Highway 401 outside Raeford, NC near Fayetteville when a Dodge pickup attempted to make a turn from oncoming traffic across Mr. Blackwell's lane of travel.  The truck struck the Bobtail causing it to roll.    The tank support on the Bobtail received damage and the unit could not be placed upright until the propane was flared off.    A 2 inch pipe nipple that screws into the back check valve on the back of the truck was leaking for a short amount of time.  After this uncontrolled release was stopped the controlled release/flare off of the tank lasted approximately 14 hours.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column42: FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTIONS, WITH NOT LESS THAN 25 PERCENT FORMALDEHYDE
column168: ON FEBRUARY 17TH, 2011 AT 22:30 A TEAM TRANSPORT (DOT ID # 599617, HAZMAT REG. #051010 563 095S) TRUCK ARRIVED AT ARCLINE SURFACES CARRYING A LOAD OF FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION (51.5%) FOR DELIVERY. THE LOAD WAS LATE IN ARRIVAL SO THE DEPARTMENT THAT UNLOADS THE TRUCK HAD ALREADY LEFT FOR THE EVENING.  INSTEAD OF NOTIFYING ARCLIN PERSONNEL OF HIS ARRIVAL THE DRIVER DECIDED TO UNLOAD THE MATERIAL, WITHOUT AUTHORIZATION OR SUPERVISION.  ARCLIN HAS PROCEDURES IN PLACE THAT DO NOT ALLOW UNLOADING AFTER HOURS.  SINCE THE DRIVER DIDN'T WANT TO WAIT UNTIL MORNING HE PRESSURIZED HIS TANKER AND PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD USING AIR PRESSURE, WHICH IS ALSO NOT ALLOWED, BECAUSE IT WAS FASTER. AT 23:30 WHEN THE UNLOAD WAS COMPLETE THE EXCESS PRESSURE ACCUMULATED IN THE STORAGE TANK AND CAUSED THE WELD ALONG THE EDGE OF THE ROOF AND SIDE WALL TO RUPTURE.  WHEN THE RUPTURE OCCURED IT CAUSED 40 POUNDS OF FORMALDEHYDE TO BELCH OUT OF THE RUPTURE ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE SEALED TANK FARM AND STARTED THE OFF GASSING OF FORMALDEHYDE VAPOR AT THE RATE OF 0.05263 POUNDS PER MINUTE.  AT THIS TIME (23:30) THE DRIVER FINALLY NOTIFIED ARCLIN THAT HE WAS THERE AND HEARD A "POP" WHILE UNLOADING, ARCLIN IMMEDIATELY ENACTED OUR EMERGENCY PROCEDURES.  THE TRUCK DRIVER LEFT SOON AFTER THIS, BEFORE ARCLIN'S HSE COORDINATOR ARRIVED ON SCENE.  THE CLEANUP AND EMPTYING OF THE TANK WAS COMPLETE AT 17:25 ON THE 18TH OF MARCH.  THE TOTAL RELEASE WAS 96.58 POUNDS, WHICH CONSISTED OF 40 POUNDS FROM THE FLOOR OF THE TANK FARM AND 56.58 POUNFS FROM THE FORMALDEHYDE VAPORS.
column169: ALL LOADING AND UNLOADING VALVES ARE NOW LOCKED WHEN NOT IN USE AND ONLY AUTHORIZED ARCLIN PERSONNEL WILL HAVE A KEY FOR THE LOCKS.  AFFECTED ARCLIN PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED AND TRAINED IN THIS CHANGE OF PROCEDURE.  THE TIMING FOR THE AUTOMATIC GATE ENTRY INTO THE FACILITY HAS ALSO BEEN MODIFIED TO DECREASE THE TIME IT IS OPEN FOR SHIFT CHANGES.

column168: During a fuel drop (regular unleaded) on 2/24/11 at approximately 1840, a customer drove over the transfer line resulting in a loss of gasoline.  The transfer was stopped and the Fire Depart., Shelby County EMA, and the Alabama Department of Environmental Management (ADEM) were notified.  Released product traveled from the underground storage tank (UST) area, east-northeast across the concrete surface and entered two storm drain inlets located along the eastern portion of the property.  Product accumulated in each drop inlet and the connector pipe.  Some product also accumulated in the discharge pipe but it did not appear to traverse through this pipe to the oulet located on the northern portion of the property.  Oil dry was applied to visually affected surface areas and a vacuum truck was used to remove product from the drop inlets.  In addition, water from the fire department truck (approximately 750 gallons) was used to flush the connector line and aid in sediment/debris removeal from the drop inlets.  Once this was completed the residual water at the bottom of the inlets appeared to be relatively clear.  Absorbent booms were placed within the storm drain at the discharge point (NE portion of property) and NE drop inlet.  It does not appear that any product was discharged from the property.
column169: Operational procedures will be evaluated and modified as necessary to prevent incidents such as this in the future.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE WITNESS, AT APPROXIMATELY 4:22 AM ON FEBRUARY 25TH 2011, HE SAW A TRACTOR TRAILER RIG MOVING WEST BOUND GO INTO THE MEDIAN AND FLIP, THEN SLIDE TO A STOP.    THE EVIDENCE AT THE SCENE INDICATES THE TRACTOR TRAILER HAS BEEN TRAVELING WEST ON INTERSTATE 30, AND LEFT THE ROADWAY ON THE LEFT SIDE SHOULDER. AS THE TRUCK WENT INTO THE CENTER MEDIAN, IT ROLLED OVER ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE AS THE TRUCK SLID INTO THE CONCRETE DRAIN. THE TRUCK CONTINUED TO ROLL ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE BEFORE COMING TO A REST. THE DRIVER WAS PRONOUNCED AT THE SCENE BY SALINE COUNTY CORONER.    ALL EMERGENCY PERSONNEL RESPONDED, INCLUDING TWO EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREWS FOR CLEANUP. THE GASOLINE LEFT THE CARGO TANK, RAN DOWN THE CONCRETE DRAIN THE TRUCK WAS IN, AND DOWN A STORM WATER DRAIN IN THE MEDIAN. THE GASOLINE THEN TRAVELED SOUTH UNDER THE EAST BOUND LANE WHERE IT BEGAN TO POOL ON TOP OF A POND. THE HAZMAT TEAM PLACED MARINE BOOMS ACROSS THE POND AND AREAS LEADING TO THE POND. THEY THEN USED VACUUM TRUCKS TO RECOVER THE GASOLINE.    THE PACKAGE FAILURE WAS A RESULT OF THE CARGO TANK SLIDING ACROSS THE CONCRETE DRAIN IN THE BOTTOM OF THE MEDIAN. THE CONCRETE RIPPED LARGE HOLES IN THE RIGHT(PASSENGER) SIDE OF THE TANK, ALLOWING MOST OF THE GASOLINE TO SPILL. THE GASOLINE RELEASE WAS GREATER AT FIRST, BUT CONTINUED TO TRICKLE OUT FOR A COUPLE OF HOURS. INITIALLY, THERE WAS NOT A SAFE WAY TO STOP THE RELEASE.
column169: WHILE THE REASON THE VEHICLE LEFT THE ROADWAY IS UNKNOWN, WE FEEL CERTAIN THAT IT WAS NOT A MECHANICAL FAILURE. THE TRACTOR WAS JUST THREE WEEKS OLD AND TRAILER SHOWED NO SIGNS OF FAILURE BESIDES THE POINTS OF IMPACT. WE HAVE DISCUSSED WITH ALL OF OUR DRIVERS POSSIBLE CAUSES AND PREVENTIONS FOR THIS INCIDENT.

column168: One CTMV was being emptied into another CTMV on the Carbolytic property. After the the two tanks were connected and the oil/water mixture began to transfer from one to the other, the attendants walked away from the CTMVs. While the attendants were gone, the pipe carrying the fluid became disconnected allowing the oil/water mixture to flow to the ground. This went on for approximately 3 hours releasing around 5,800 gallons of the oil/water mixture. Immediately after discovery, NRC was called. Carbolytic was directed to call a HAZMAT crew who then contacted the Missouri Department of Natural Resources.
column169: To prevent future spills from the CTMVs, Carbolytic is providing more training to their employees concerning the unloading of hazardous materials. Carbolytic is also going to start locking the CTMVs so that only authorized individuals will have access to them.

column168: Company driver was unloading a shipment at the consignee when he noticed that one of the drums in the order was leaking.  Upon inspection of the freight he saw that the E-track clip on a load securement strap had gouged a hole in the upper chime of the drum.  The clip was positioned between the drum and the side of the trailer.  The motion during the transportation of the drum from the shipper location to the consignee location apparently forced the clip into the chime resulting in a small leak of less than 2 liquid gallons.  The driver obtained his overpack from underneath his trailer and placed the damaged drum inside with the assistance from consignee employees.  The spilled material was cleaned up by the driver.  The overpack was labeled and brought back to the shipping facility for disposition.    The spilled material was determined to be unsalable and was disposed of with other branch waste materials.
column169: Shipper/carrier employees were informed of this incident during regularly scheduled safety meetings.  Shipper employees were instructed to avoid placing the clip on the chime and also to position the clip to ensure that it will not become trapped between the side of the trailer and the freight.  A specific labeled location has been created for returned damaged goods to ensure a timely inspection and disposition of questionable goods in the future.  The returned goods authorization (RGA) process will be reviewed with all personnel to assure that an RGA is created immediately for any damaged and undelivered product(s).

Driver called dispatch and dispatch called 911.  Woodstock Police arrived and evacuated neighbors, Ulster County HAZMAT  assisted. Bottini employees arrived at scene and discovered the strainer leaking propane. Wet towels were wrapped around the strainer which froze and contained the  leak. Bottini employees determined that the internal valve was closed and remaining  propane safely bled off. The truck was then driven to Amthor's Welding to make repairs.
column169: Check the strainers at each preventative maintenance and replace as needed.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Human Error
column168: Fly Ash was transported from CT to NY in a dry bulk trailer to a rail trans-load facility.  Material was being unloaded from the dry bulk trailer and then immediately loaded into a rail car for subsequent delivery to a facility in WA state. The rail trans-load facility was responsible for transferring the fly ash from the dry bulk trailer to the rail car according to the contract.  However, the driver of the dry bulk trailer was asked to assist by the rail trans-load facility and this request for assistance was not made known to the highway carrier.  During the transfer of the fly ash from the dry bulk trailer, material began to leak out at the hose connection at the rear of the dry bulk trailer.  The driver of the dry bulk trailer attempted to assist the facility operators and secure the hose connection, but the hose completely disconnected from the dry bulk trailer.  Approximately 1800 to 2000 pounds of fly ash was spilled to the ground surface.  The dry bulk trailer driver and two people from the rail trans-load facility were covered in dust.  The driver had the fly ash dust rinsed-off and then went to the hospital to be examined but was not admitted.  To the best of our knowledge, the two rail trans-load personnel did not go to the hospital and had the fly ash dust rinsed-off at their facility.
column169: Operator should have shut-off the blower, bleed off any pressure and completely stopped the unloading of the fly ash before attempting to secure the loose hose connection at the rear of the dry bulk trailer.
